I have an inherent problem with cEDH as a concept since its goal is to mix/max a format created specifically to get away from the other forms of competitive Magic. This tension naturally leads to conflict with more casual players when they mix (intentional or not).

There are formats that already do what cEDH does and they do it better in an environment with no chance for accidental pubstomping. That always leads me to be heavily suspicious of the true motivations of most cEDH players. I don’t doubt there are sorority houses that happen to also be the best place in the neighborhood to birdwatch but I’m still gonna be really suspicious of your motivations when I see you lurking in the bushes with binoculars outside Kappa Alpha Theta.

It's people that want to act like they're "better players" but really aren't because the folks that consistently play legacy wipe the floor with them, so they have to wipe the floor w/ casuals instead.

It’s odd because the outlet for someone’s competitive streak exists and a format that, whether you agree or not, is based by the founders as being casual in nature so trying to push it in a more competitive vein creates the various, and well covered, problems when the two versions mix. 

Honestly cEDH should have a different name and ban list since it’s a very different format.

Let’s be clear, folks can do what they want, but wanting to min/max a format designed to be closer to kitchen table only works if your entire meta is on board and shouldn’t be a goal if you play with a wider and more varied group.

On the point about the original intent of EDH, I think the point is moot. Nobody is playing for the founders any more. Thousands of players have put their own spin on the format, and that's not exclusive to the cEDH community.

As to the second point, sure, I guess it makes sense for cEDH to re-label itself and come up with its own ban list. Things have been working out for them as is, though. Like I said, and like I think most people recognize, the issue is one of individual personalities. A decent person with a cEDH deck isn't going to pubstomp with it. A not-decent person will pubstomp.
It's probably significant that the cEDH community around me has organized play and generally don't play their competitive decks outside that space.
There are bi-weekly cEDH tournaments that aren't supported by the LGS but still well attended.

My playgroup is an interesting place as we all are competitive but want to do completely insane plays so we kind of self limit as we min max a very odd strategy or combo, it isn't about going just for the kill, we like to style it. But if someone wants to play more casual, we can play it more casually, if they want to go hard, we can go hard. I think that dividing cEDH and EDH could cause a dissonance between the two groups, it really needs to be a community based thing
The dissonance already exists. Mixing decks from the two generally leads to unfun games on both sides.

So what I'm reading in this entire exchange is that the problems only arise when there is a massive power imbalance in decks at any given table. That is an issue even within "casual" EDH when someone brings a pubstompy deck like Azusa, while someone is playing Depala vehicles.
